deck_excerpt: Sky Striker Pure • Control • Can go 1st / 2nd
deck_description:
This is a pretty standard take on Sky Striker, so I do not believe that explaining the strategy is necessary. The differences in this list are that it focuses more on the Salamangreat matchup with d.d. crow at 2 (you can play it at 3) and shark cannon at 1 with one-sided (you can main deck it at 2 and then play 3 shared ride in the side deck for the mirror). The side deck is geared towards Thunder, but you can tailor it for other matchups as well. As Sky Striker stands, it really only has to worry about three matchups; Thunder Dragons, the mirror & Salamangreat. However, I will provide this resource for players newly returning to the deck or just recently introduced(I find that the rhetoric discussed here is applicable to a wide variety of strategies but especially relevant with this deck.): https://ygoprodeck.com/advanced-sky-striker-strategies/ Card Breakdown:
  • Raye: Your Normal Summon -- her quick effect allows you to use to activate the effects of Area Zero & Multirole while maintaining advantage (Tribute after target).
  • Hornet Drones: A token to Summon your Striker Links & to help with OTKs
  • Area Zero: A field spell that can Special Summon Raye from your Deck or potentially add a Sky Striker card
  • Vector Blast: Can clear your opponent's Extra Monster Zone & sets up your GY
  • Engage: Pot of Greed
  • Shark Cannon: A pseudo-D.D. Crow
  • Afterburners: Monster Removal / Pseudo Back row Removal
  • Jamming Wave: Back row Removal / Pseudo Monster REmoval
  • Eagle Eye: Protection
  • Widow Anchor: Monster negate
  • Multirole: Next turn setup & protection
  • Hercules Base: Recursion

deck_excerpt: just summon dark magician and banish cards
deck_description: revolving around summoning dark magician with your card effects and banishing your enemies cards

The goal of this deck is to emphasize the sky striker engine in a time where integrating the striker engine has become quite hard to mesh with as drones is at 1 and Trickstar relies heavily on its normal summon of Candina. The way that this deck handles the issue of drones at 1 is that it offers the player a choice; you can either use your normal summon on raye (should you fail to get to drones) or you can use your normal summon on Candina (should you get Candina). Despite this limiting the player to 1 or the other, as far as engines go, it does allow the player manning the deck to play both engines as the duel progresses. Generally speaking, it would be smarter to set up a sky striker field of widow anchors with some disruption for the next turn - but it's up to each player to choose the engine. Side Notes:
  • To improve the Trickstar engine, one could play Carobein at 1 - 2, cut Raye to 0, and move widow to 2.
  • Afterburners and Jamming Wave are interchangeable; I've put Jamming Wave over Afterburner because it destroys without targeting.
  • The destrudo engine could be played (destrudo + mare mare) to add removal following the transition from sky striker to Trickstar
  • The side deck can include gameciel, and it can change the hand trap ratio
  • This deck is pretty reliant on knowing your matchup; and with that being said, cherries can be the win condition of this deck in many matchups.
Plays of Note:
  • Candina Normal Summon:  Search Lycorris or Reincarnation, or Lilybell later in the game
  • Add Lilybell: Special Summon Lilybell, attack --> Add Lycorris, Lycorris tag out Lilybell <-- this generates much needed offense
  • Normal Candina + Reincarnation in GY: Candina searches Lilybell, Lilybell add Lycorris, make Link 2, activate Reincarnation from GY --> make Link 3 [double knightmare]
Other cards that should be considered:
  • Gozen Match
  • Rivalry of Warlords
  • Gamma & Driver
  • Ghost Belle
  • Ghost Ogre
  • Kaijus

deck_excerpt: It's almost a complete lockdown of the game.
deck_description:
Deck Created By: Big Crunch (Deck Inspiration: ???) Main Goal: Summon both Naturia Exterio and Last Warrior From Another Planet to perform a lockdown How to Accomplish: Use the monsters to swarm the field and thin the deck until you get to Cyber-Stein and other important pieces Monsters
  • Danger! Cards - Use to swarm the field (Especially with Dogman and Nessie) and thin out the deck. Keep using it until you have all the important pieces.
  • Dr. Frankenderp -  Use the card and then activate the effect to draw a card. Normal Summon it or Special Summon using Saryuja. (You can only use the effect once)
  • Blackwing - Zephyros the Elite - Use it to return an important monster card or Temple of the Kings/Brain Research Lab (if you use it instead of Telekinetic Charging Cell) if its on the graveyard. (You can only use the effect to Special Summon once) (Extra monster to Normal Summon if necessary)
  • Blackwing - Steam the Cloak - Use it to summon tokens (Saryuja can help) and to help a bit on swarming (it summons tokens). (You can tribute a card to Special Summon it from the Graveyard) (You can only Special Summon it once) (Extra monster to Normal Summon if necessary)
  • Broww, Huntsman of Dark World - If discarded, a card is added (Extra monster to Normal Summon if necessary)
  • Shaddoll Beast - If discarded, a card is added (Only once though)
  • Beiige, Vanguard of Dark World - If discard, it summons itself (Good with swarming) (Extra monster to Normal Summon if necessary)
Draw Spells
  • Upstart Goblin - Hand neutral card (Helps with thinning)
  • Allure of Darkness - Hand neutral card (Helps with thinning and removing unecessary Dark cards)
  • Card Destruction - Card that replaces your entire hand with new cards (Don't send the important cards unless if its necessary. Don't discard Cyber-Stein ever) (Use it if hand is bad, hand is filled with discard cards or when hand is filled with many cards) (Helps with thinning a lot if in a right moment)
  • The Beginning of the End - A +2 card when Graveyard is filled with Dark monsters (7+ Dark cards to be precise) (Helps with thinning and drawing) (Avoid using two at the same time unless the Graveyard is filled)
  • One Day of Peace - A card that allows you to draw a card and prevents damage (Its helpful if things goes sour)
After that, you can go to these Extra Deck cards
  •  Mecha Phantom Beast Dracossack - A mini Galaxy Tomahawk. Use it to swarm the field with tokens. (A mini Swarmer)
  • Saryuja Skull Dread - Use it to refill your hand with new cards and get rid unecessary ones. (Summon it using 4 monsters [most of the time] unless its really necessary)
  • Wee Witch's Apprentice - A two arrowed Link monster that is good for having two Extra Deck monsters (Also a Dark monster)
  • Space Insulator - A Link monster that can use any monster for summon (Good when tokens are out) (Also a Dark monster)
  • Link Spider - Good for token renaming (For Saryuja)
  Then, here are the card you need  at most or all of the time
  • Cyber-Stein - The most important playmaker. When the perfect conditions are met, use it to summon the 2 Fusion cards (don't put Cyber-Stein to zones that will block the link pointers, put it in the middle of either of the two Extra Monster Zone below)
  • Temple of the Kings - use it to activate Dimension Guardian when conditions are met
  • Dimension Guardian - use it and equip it to Exterio to avoid being destroyed by Last Warrior from Another Planet
  • Brain Research Lab/Telekinetic Charging Cell - Use it to avoid paying Cyber-Stein's cost (use it on Cyber-Stein)
  • Localized Tornado  - A semi-important card. Use it before your opponent's Main Phase so Exterio can have multiple negates.
  • Reprodocus - Use it to Cyber-Stein to change its type to Psychic (Make sure that Cyber-Stein is below the link pointer)
  • Naturia Exterio - Must be the first Fusion card to be summoned by Cyber-Stein. You must equip Dimensional Guardian to this card so it can avoid being destroyed by the other Fusion card. This card can negate Spell and Trap Cards below Spell Speed 3 (if conditions are not met, you can make Cyber-Stein summon this card if your opponent is Spell Card/ Trap Card heavy)
  • Last Warrior from Another Planet - Summon it after Exterio. Summon this card using Cyber-Stein. This card prevents all kinds of summons (but not set) (if conditions are not met, you can make Cyber-Stein summon this card if your opponent is Monster heavy)
  • LANphorhynchus - After using Reprodocus, link it and a monster to summon this card. This will indicate where the 2 Fusion monsters will set place.
  The main problem of this is that it can't avoid Set monster cards and Spell Speed 3 or 4 cards. It can also be disrupted if your opponent controls something that can destroy Last Warrior or Dimension Guardian (it will affect Exterio)

deck_excerpt: This is the best way to make Red-eyes Competitive In my opinion
deck_description:
This deck is more of a Spam build that was made by your truly. this deck was made to help get out a rank 7 spam with a small synchron engine to help boost up the deck with more speed. in this deck profile, I'm going to discuses my card choices and card ratios and there purpose. there will also be a combo section of the article where I will explain the various/main combos of the deck.

The deck

the deck obviously consists of 3 red-eyes cards not just because the dark is very nostalgic, but it is also very necessary for the deck; and yes there is a small Danger! engine in the deck, but the reason for it (besides the extra names for skull dread) is because the deck also consists of a Rank 7 spam in order to get out Dracossac and Red-Eyes Flare Metal Dragon. the synchron engine is probably my favorite engine in any deck, the reason why I have this in the deck is because we need crystron needle fiber to help boost the decks consistency, Not to mention rocket synchron is also a nice tuner to help go into Savage dragon. The other reason why rocket synchron is in there is because it is easy material for the Guardragon engine(WARNING: this is NOT a Red-eyes Guardragon deck). yes there are some times where you can brick with the deck, but that is what the hand traps are for. the hand traps in the deck(2 ash blossom and 2 ghost ogre) can also help keep your opponents searching and field presents under control, they can also be used as a target for needlefiber incase you run out of synchron/ glow-up bulb targets.

The Side Deck

The side deck can be useful in todays metagame, but I wouldn't recommend running them unless you absolutely have to, of course you can just run them by preference. just to point out the obvious, we have extra copies of ash blossom and ghost ogre and effect valor incase you need to be a little more control based with the deck. Pankratops is good in the deck as well, but the problem with it in this specific build  is because if your playing dangers, you have to play pankratops first and then go off with your Danger!/Synchron engine so you wont be able to get its effects off after. I do run an extra copy of nessie and the snek boi in case I feel a little cheeky, or in case I need the extra summoning power. however this can come back to bite you because sometimes messing the ratios of the deck can lead to bricks in the deck, but that is why the hand traps are there. and extra quick launch is always good if you need extra turbo, twin twisters is good for backrow hate, world legacy guardragons is good to get your level 1 dragons out of the GY, and infinite impermanence is good for more control of the board as well as red reboot which is for the altergiets. there was also deep consideration on wheather I should put dragon ravine in here as well, but the problem is that you need to have full access to the deck in order to make it work, which means that you can exactly send as many cards to the GY as you want...also there aren't that many dragon in the deck to send to the GY.

The Extra Deck

there is not really much to say about the extra deck except that is just your casual guardragon extra deck with the link monsters, summon sorc, and skull dread. the other monsters such as Beelze and black rose dragon are in there just to spice up the deck a bit. but the important monster in the deck is "Red-eyes Flare Metal Dragon". the reason why this card is the important one(Besides Dracossac) is because this can not only burn your opponent, but I can also special summon a red-eyes monster from the GY for another name. In fact, flare metal is SO important in the deck that he is part of the main combo for the deck.

Combos

Even though the deck is very flexible with out the main combo, it is best to use this combo as much as you can, which I will explain now.
  •  the main combo should at least include one tuner, and one or more danger! card, first you summon the tuner(in this case glow-up bulb), use it to summon linkuriboh and the needle fiber, use needlefibers effect to summon rokket synchron. then use the danger! monster to special summon(if your opponent hits jackalope that is fine) itself or another monster, then use rokket synchron to summon Elpy and the danger! and needle fiber to summon triple burst. you then summon darkness metal and go into your casual guardragon plays from there, by the time you get to skull dread, you shoudl be able to at least have a red-eyes and/or Extra deck monster on board.

Conclusion

so...what do I think of the deck? I think it's pretty good, the only issues I see is the fact that the deck is more or less combo oriented than other decks such as altergiest. as long as you can get a synchron plus another danger! in hand, then you should be completely fine. the only other issue is that the deck must go first so it can have time to set up like any other deck. if I wanted to change anything, I would swap out a tuning for 2 or more impermanence just so I can be better protected. welp, that was my deck profile. I am still experimenting with this deck, but I do hope that this can be a good starting point for other red-eyes players like me, but if you do want to play something other than "Red-eyes degenerate link cluster F***" than you can look at my pure red-eyes guardragon deck profile which should be s little easier to get a grip on. hope you guys like the deck.

deck_excerpt: Graydle Control with brand new playstyle!
deck_description:
Use your Graydle monster and other Tuner to keep Link and Synchro Summon monsters for OTK. There are 3 main strategies for this build:
  • Control: Using Graydle monsters to attack your opponent monsters, take some battle damage, then control your opponent, then use them to attack again. (Don't do this against unaffected/cannot be targeted monsters, because you can't control them)
 
  • OTK: By continuously using monsters to Link Summon, then activate Graydle Slime monster to destroy Graydle Dragon and a Graydle card, so you can Synchro Summon 2 monster Level 8 Synchro Monster (usually Graydle Dragon and Stardust Dragon) then attack your opponent.
 
  • Field Lock: Using multiple Graydle monsters (especially Graydle Slime Jr.) to protect you from attack, then control monsters your opponent control (in case you have lack of monsters, activate Graydle Parasite for more), then after a few turns, when you have enough card(s) for a combo, you should use monsters you have to Link Summon then OTK your opponent.
Please comment below if you have any questions, and if you like this, give a thumb up!

deck_excerpt: A Synchro WATER based deck revolving around the White Aura monsters.
deck_description: In my quest to create a new The Legendary Fisherman III deck I ended up just making a bit of a Synchro WATER deck. It's not great, there isn't any really strong win condition of the deck. It mainly revolves around the White Aura monsters and flooding the field a bit.   Neptabyss, the Atlantean Prince can easily discard a Atlantean Dragoons to then do a few things. You can pull a Lappis Dragon to have it immediately summon or you can do what I prefer and pull another copy of Atlantean Dragoons and then use Mermail Abyssmegalo to discard that copy (and then pull a Lappis Dragon). The Legendary Fisherman III is a great card if you can get it out but don't bank on it. Instead try to use it with Tatsunoko to summon White Aura Bihamut. Crystron Needlefiber can use his effect to summon either Coral Dragon or Ib the World Chalice Miko (which can then pull World Legacy Succession). One for One usually goes int Neptabyss, the Atlantean Prince. I really like Sea Stealth Attack since it got released but I've found myself struggling to get it out with A Legendary Ocean. Plenty of work can be done to improve this but I am currently releasing it as is!

deck_excerpt: One-card True King of All Calamities using Orcusts.
deck_description:
The goal of this Deck is to turbo out The True King of All Calamities using The Phantom Knight's Rank Up-Magic. Preferably using Destroymare Iblee to Link Summon into Troymare Mermaid for a 1 card combo True King of all Calamities. However, this Deck is susceptible to many hand traps, potentially ending your combos. At the start of the game, utilize your many Turbo cards to Link Summon into Troymare Mermaid. After that, you can follow these steps for an easy combo:
  • On summon, activate Troymare Mermaid's effect to discard 1 card; Special Summon Orphegel Troymare
  • Link Summon Orphegel Galatea using Troymare Mermaid and Orphegel Troymare
  • In the GY, use Orphegel Troymare's effect to banish itself and send Orphegel Diver to the GY
  • In the GY, activate Orphegel Diver's effect to banish itself and Special Summon Orphegel Scherzone
  • Activate Orphegel Galatea's effect to shuffle 1 banished Machine-Type monsters and set Orphegel Babel
  • Using Orphegel Galatea and Orphegel Scherzone, Link Summon into The Phantom Knights of Rusty Bardiche
  • Activate The Phantom Knights of Rusty Bardiche's effect to send The Phantom Knight's Silent Boots to the GY, then set Phantom Knight's Fog Blade
  • In the GY, activate The Phantom Knight's Silent Boots to banish itself and add The Phantom Knights' Rank Up-Magic Launch
  • In the GY, activate Orphegel Scherzone to banish itself and Special Summon Orphegel Galatea from the GY
  • Using Orphegel Galatea as Overlay Material, Xyz Summon Sheorphegel Dingirsu to a zone The Phantom Knights of Rusty Bardiche points to
  • On Sheorphegel Dingirsu's summon (DO NOT ACTIVATE HIS EFFECT), The Phantom Knights of Rusty Bardiche will activate to target and destroy 1 card on the field.
  • Target Sheorphegel Dingirsu, but detach one Xyz Material to prevent it's destruction
  • Activate The Phantom Knights' Rank Up-Magic Launch to Xyz Summon The True King of All Calamities using Sheorphegel Dingirsu

deck_excerpt: Trickstar OTK Synchro Turbo (Going First or Second)
deck_description: I know its been a while since I've posted a new deck but I've been testing for you guys for some really cool spicy decks and I wanted my other decks to get more views and kinda sink in. I like to give decks time and then post a new one so everyone has a chance to check it out! Anyways I was looking at Destrudo The Lost Dragon's Frisson and was thinking if there's anything cool to do with him since he's a really good synchro turbo card and then I saw Shooting Riser Dragon which is a level 7 tuner that can synchro summon during your opponent's turn. I saw that and noticed how it's effect says it can reduce its own level by a monster you send from deck to grave and realized you can use that plus another monster to make Black Rose Dragon during your opponent's turn to blow up their field which is pretty crazy. Anyways, this deck can go first or second it doesn't really matter. Going first you have many tools at your disposal like the Black Rose Dragon play I just explained and triple Trickstar Reincarnation as well as the three Solemns. Going second you can make Yazi, Evil of The Yang Zing with Destrudo and a Trickstar monster and summon Mare Mare and go into Borrelsword Dragon to OTK. I wanted to make a Trickstar deck that can go either first or second that is pretty consistent for you guys. I know you guys like my other Trickstar decks but I'm hoping you guys will love this one. The reason for Hack Worm is for the Destrudo Shooting Riser Dragon play I explained in the beginning. It's a free monster to special summon going first that allows you to use for Shooting Riser Dragon after you go through your Trickstar cards in hand. Another way to bring out Black Rose Dragon without Hack Worm is by using Trickstar Reincarnation in your graveyard during your opponent's main phase 1 to special summon a Trickstar monster from grave and then Shooting Riser Dragon and that Trickstar monster to synchro into Black Rose Dragon. I really hope you guys enjoy this deck and stick around for new decks weekly.

Yugo, spelled Hugo (Yūgo) in the Japanese version, is a character in the Yu-Gi-Oh! ARC-V anime. deck_excerpt: A D/D/D deck made for the link format
deck_description: This is an aggro deck that focuses on swarming the field. It can perform many combos and never bricks. D/D savant Copernicus This card is the decks' main combo starter and is extremely flexible. If you draw this card on your first turn and one other D/D card you can combo into either a zefra metaltron or a D/D/D abyss king gilgamesh. The first combo ends with D/D/D abyss king gilgamesh a full scale and the D/D savant copernicus on the field. Start by normal summoning D/D savant copernicus and use its effect to send D/D swirl slime to the graveyard then banish it and special summon any D/D monster from your hand. Use both D/D monsters on the field to go into D/D/D abyss king gilgamesh and activate his effect to set a pendulum scale. I usually use D/D/D destiny king zero larplace and D/D savant newton. You can then pendulum summon the D/D savant copernicus back from the extra deck as well as any other D/D monsters in your hand.  The second combo requires you to start with D/D savant copernicus and one other D/D monster or dark contract in hand. Normal summon D/D savant copernicus and send D/D lamia to the graveyard. Then use D/D lamia's effect to special summon itself from the graveyard. Using both monsters go into crystron needlefiber using his effect special summon a second copy of D/D lamia from your deck. Using this D/D lamia go into Linkuriboh, then using both crystron needlefiber and Linkuriboh as materials special summon zefra metaltron. D/D swirl slime D/D swirl slime is one of the best combo starters in the deck as it gets you two monsters on the field for the cost of two monsters in hand. Usually, when you start with swirl slime you fusion summon straight into D/D/D flame king genghis or D/D/D flame king high genghis and then special summon another monster straight out of your hand. This card is usually the target for cards like foolish burial and D/D savant copernicus because it can special summon any D/D monster from your hand. D/D/D abyss king gilgamesh I usually try to make this card on my first turn to set my pendulum scales. After this the card kind of just sits there the best thing to do after you summon D/D/D abyss king gilgamesh is let your opponent destroy it this lets you special summon a D/D monster from your extra deck or graveyard in defence position ignoring it's summoning conditions. I usually special summon D/D/D super doom king bright armageddon off of this effect as it stops your opponent from being able to disassemble your board with it's protection effect also it's high stat line usually means your opponent won't be able to destroy it by battle.

deck_excerpt: Easy utopia/Link spam deck for people who like Xyz monsters
deck_description:
this deck is plane and simple, you use the level 4 monsters to link/xyz summon into utopia and any other monster in the extra deck. the best combo is to
  • summon neo space connector, summon butterspys
  • use connecters effect to summon aqua dolphin
  • use aqua dolphin to reveal hand to make sure there aren't any hand traps
  • summon Isolde using neos and dolphin
  • use Isolde's effect to summon another level 4(mainly "destiny HERO - Draw guy")
  • summon utopia and continue with your casual utopia plays.
this deck can easily otk with the utopia double combo, not to mention that you can also go into an easy 4k beater (utopic dragon) assuming you have a rank-up-magic card in your hand. the deck was really fun to make, especially since I got to mix a lot of cards together from different archtypes to make this work(mainly Crusadia and Destiny HERO). you can also use other cards such as the ZW in the side deck so you can power up the Utopia monsters with other effects, but I find them a bit bricky because the only good ones in my opinion are tornado bringer and lightning blade(they are level 5's).

One of the Seven Barian Emperors sworn to destroy Astral World. Unable to use his true powers in the human world, he mind controls Duelists to collect Numbers for him. When fighting in his Barian Form, he crushes his foes with "Number 106: Giant Hand".

Pendulum Scale

 

  A Pendulum Scale (Japanese:Pendyuramu Sukēru, abbreviated in card text) (abbreviated as "PS" or "PSC" in the manga) is a set of indicators unique to Pendulum Monsters. Two of them are located above the "Monster Effect" text box of the Pendulum Monster, with the "Pendulum Effect" of the Pendulum Monster placed between them. All Pendulum Monsters have two Pendulum Scale values, signified by the blue symbol for the left, and the red symbol for the right.

  • Inferno Tempest + D.D. Dynamite (usually) = K.O.
  • Lava Golem, Unicorn, Cerberus, or Phoenix are a good way to help clear the field if needed.
  • With all the banishing you'll be doing expect Gren Maju to easily get over 10k attack. Just punch for game.

Pendulum Monster

Pendulum Monster (Japanese: ペンデュラムモンスター Pendyuramu Monsutā; usually abbreviated Ｐ（ペンデュラム）モンスター), also called a Pendulum Card in the early episodes of the Yu-Gi-Oh! ARC-V anime, is a type of Monster Card that is half green. They first appeared in the Yu-Gi-Oh! ARC-V anime, and were introduced to the OCG and TCG in Starter Deck 2014 and Super Starter: Space-Time Showdown respectively. In addition to normal usages, a Pendulum Monster can also be activated from the hand as a Spell Card in a Pendulum Zone; if there are Pendulum Monsters in both Pendulum Zones, the player can perform a Pendulum Summon. So far, Normal, Effect, Fusion, Synchro and Xyz Pendulum Monsters have been seen. Pendulum Monsters can also be Tuner, Flip and Spirit monsters.

Alito is a character appearing in the Yu-Gi-Oh! ZEXAL anime. He is an Emperor from the Barian World, working to gather the "Numbers" to prevent his world's destruction.[5] Contrary to his mission, Alito became a friendly rival of Yuma Tsukumo's at one point. Alito uses a "Battlin' Boxer" Deck, utilizing various cards to swarm the field such as "Battlin' Boxer Sparrer" and "Ring Announcer" for Xyz Summons and others to negate Trap Cards such as "Counter Clash" and "Fancy Footwork". He also uses several cards devoted to detaching Overlay Units such as "Overlay Flash" and "Xyz Block", primarily to power up his "Battlin' Boxer Lead Yoke". During his Tag-Team Duel with Nistro, he focuses on a more defensive approach, while letting Nistro take the risks of using "Number 54: Lion Heart". Here, he uses Level 3 "Battlin' Boxer" monsters named after illegal boxing maneuvers, while his "Battlin' Boxer Cheat Commissioner" Xyz Monster is based on corrupt boxing manager, reflecting how he used Nistro. Alito later gains the ability to perform a Chaos Draw, giving him access to "Rank-Up-Magic - The Seventh One", allowing him to easily Special Summon his "Number C105: Battlin' Boxer Comet Cestus", which he later augments with "Number 80: Rhapsody in Berserk" and "Number C80: Requiem in Berserk". I included Nistro's card's since he originally possessed Lion Heart
